# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: digby-mclaren
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:digby-mclaren/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:digby-mclaren/albert-w-bally] Bally started his career at Shell Oil Company, retiring as Chief Geologist after 27 years in 1981.
[src:digby-mclaren/albert-w-bally] After retirement, he joined Rice University as chair of the Department of Geology and Geophysics.
[src:digby-mclaren/albert-w-bally] He remained active in the department until his death in 2019.
[src:digby-mclaren/albert-w-bally] In 1988, Bally was elected President of the Geological Society of America.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-gordon-mckay] Born in Toronto, Ontario, McKay graduated from Upper Canada College in 1942.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-gordon-mckay] He received a Bachelor of Arts degree in 1946 from the University of Toronto, a Master of Arts degree in 1947 from Yale University, a A.M. degree in 1948 from Princeton University and a Ph.D. in 1950 from Princeton.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-gordon-mckay] He started his academic career as an instructor at Princeton University from 1947 to 1949.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-gordon-mckay] He started teaching at McMaster University in 1957.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-gordon-mckay] He was appointed an associate professor in 1959, a full professor in 1961, and retired as a Professor Emeritus in 1990.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-gordon-mckay] He was chair of Classics from 1962 to 1968 and from 1976 to 1979.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-gordon-mckay] From 1968 to 1973, he was the founding dean of the Faculty of Humanities.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-gordon-mckay] He was president of the Royal Society of Canada from 1984 to 1987.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-gordon-mckay] After his retirement from McMaster University in 1990, he taught at York University in Toronto as adjunct professor of humanities from 1990 until 1996.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-gordon-mckay] In 1965, he was made a Fellow of the Royal Society of Canada.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-gordon-mckay] He was a recipient of the Queen Elizabeth II Silver Jubilee Medal, the Canadian Centennial Medal, and the 125th Anniversary of the Confederation of Canada Medal.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-gordon-mckay] In 1988, he was made an Officer of the Order of Canada in recognition for being a "distinguished scholar, educator and humanitarian".
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-gordon-mckay] He received honorary degrees from the University of Manitoba (1986), Brock University (1990), Queen's University (1991), McMaster University (1992), and the University of Waterloo (1993).
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] Winchell graduated from the Wesleyan University of Middletown, Connecticut, in 1847.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] He then taught at Pennington Male Seminary of New Jersey, Amenia Seminary of New York (where he had previously been a student), an academy in Newbern, Alabama, and the Mesopotamia Female Seminary of Eutaw, the last of which was founded by him.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] He became president of the Masonic University at Selma, Alabama, in 1853.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] He was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1865.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] In 1854 Winchell entered the service of the University of Michigan as professor of physics and civil engineering.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] Eventually he became professor of geology and paleontology at Michigan.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] In 1859, Winchell was appointed as State Geologist of Michigan for the newly formed second geological survey of the state.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] He held the post until 1863 when the state did not appropriate funding to continue the survey.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] The survey was resumed in 1869, and Winchell was reappointed in April.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] Owing to conflicting opinions between Winchell and his superiors, he resigned in 1871.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] In 1863 Winchell took up a lease on a cotton plantation near Vicksburg, Mississippi, under a plan devised by Gen.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] Lorenzo Thomas to lease plantations along the Mississippi River to loyal men from the North, who would hire black laborers on terms prescribed by the army.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] Winchell organized the Ann Arbor Cotton Company and sold stock to the university's president, whereupon he received a leave of absence to engage in cotton planting.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] General Thomas set wages at a low level ($7 per month for men, $5 for women, minus the cost of medical attention and clothing).
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] Even then, many lessees defrauded the freedmen of their earnings.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] In the winter of 1863–64, the Treasury Department briefly assumed control of the Mississippi Valley labor system, mandated a substantial increase in black wages, and contemplated leasing the plantations directly to the freedmen.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] The venture brought him only problems, and after he returned to Michigan in 1864, his brother Martin, who was managing the plantation, was killed by guerrillas.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] In 1872, he was appointed chancellor of Syracuse University.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] The depression of 1873 affected both his personal finances and those of Syracuse, and these troubles led him to resign this position in 1874.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] In 1875, he worked as a professor of geology and zoology at Vanderbilt University.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] There, his views on evolution, as expressed in his book *Adamites and Preadamites: or, A Popular Discussion* (1878), were not acceptable to the University administration because they diverged from Biblical teaching.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] Today the views on the "inferiority of the Negro" (quote from his 1878 book) would probably have been the focus of controversy.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] In any case, he was obligated to resign in 1878.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] In 1888, he co-founded the Geological Society of America in Ithaca, New York along with John J.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] He served as the 3rd president of GSA in 1891.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] He then returned to the University of Michigan, where he was professor of geology and paleontology.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] His work in geology was not so significant as his teaching and popular lectures and writing in this field.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] He was much concerned with reconciling science and religion.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] He was an advocate of theistic evolution.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] The fish **Clear chub** *Hybopsis winchelli* (Girard, 1856) is named after him.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] The University of Michigan named a wing of the West Quad dormitory after Winchell, and Ann Arbor honored him with Winchell Park, a neighborhood park on the city's east side.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] Winchell's name was removed from the dormitory in 2018, and the park was renamed after former Ann Arbor Public Schools board president Harold J.
[src:digby-mclaren/alexander-winchell] In removing Winchell's name, the university described his *Preadamites* as an "unambiguously racist" work.
[src:digby-mclaren/alfred-church-lane] Lane was educated at Harvard University and received his A.B. degree in 1883.
[src:digby-mclaren/alfred-church-lane] Between 1883 and 1885 he taught mathematics at Harvard, then studied at the University of Heidelberg until 1887 before returning to Harvard to earn his Ph.D. in 1888.
[src:digby-mclaren/alfred-church-lane] The following year he joined the Michigan State Geologic Survey as a petrographer, and he remained in that post into 1892 while also serving as an instructor at the Michigan College of Mines.
[src:digby-mclaren/alfred-church-lane] He became assistant state geologist for Michigan in 1892, and from 1899 to 1909 he was the state geologist.
[src:digby-mclaren/alfred-church-lane] Finally, he joined Tufts College in 1892, becoming the Pearson professor of geology and mineralogy.
[src:digby-mclaren/alfred-church-lane] He retired from the college in 1936 as professor emeritus.
[src:digby-mclaren/alfred-church-lane] While at Tufts, he served as vice president of the AAAS Division of Geology in 1907.
[src:digby-mclaren/alfred-church-lane] He received an honorary D.Sc. from Tufts in 1913.
[src:digby-mclaren/alfred-church-lane] From 1922 and 1946 he was chairman for the Committee on the Measurement of Geologic Time for the National Research Council.
[src:digby-mclaren/alfred-church-lane] He served as a member of the Board of Visitors at Harvard Observatory in 1924.
[src:digby-mclaren/alfred-church-lane] Alfred Lane was appointed as consultant of science to the Library of Congress in 1929; the first person to hold that post.
[src:digby-mclaren/alfred-church-lane] In 1931, he was president of the Geological Society of America.
[src:digby-mclaren/alfred-church-lane] He was awarded the Ballou Medal by Tufts College in 1940 for "distinguished service to education and the nation".
[src:digby-mclaren/alfred-church-lane] During his career, he authored 1,087 publications.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] The **American Philosophical Society** (**APS**) is an American scholarly organization and learned society founded in 1743 in Philadelphia that promotes knowledge in the humanities and natural sciences through research, professional meetings, publications, library resources, and community outreach.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] It was founded by the polymath Benjamin Franklin and is considered the first learned society founded in what became the United States.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, the society's headquarters and a museum, is located just east of Independence Hall in Independence National Historical Park.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] In 1965, in recognition of the building's history, it was designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] The society has about 1,000 elected members.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] As of April 2020, 5,710 members had been inducted since its creation.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] Through research grants, published journals, the American Philosophical Society Museum, an extensive library, and regular meetings, the society supports a variety of disciplines in the humanities and the sciences.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] The American Philosophical Society was founded as the **Philosophical Society** in 1743 by Benjamin Franklin, James Alexander, Francis Hopkinson, John Bartram, Philip Syng Jr., and others as an offshoot of an earlier club, the Junto.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] It was common at the time for intellectual societies to invite members from around the world, where the society recruited members from other countries, including Alexander von Humboldt, the Marquis de Lafayette, Baron von Steuben, Tadeusz Kościuszko, and Princess Dashkova.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] The society lapsed into inactivity by 1746, but was revived in 1767.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] On January 2, 1769, the society united with the American Society for Promoting Useful Knowledge under the name **American Philosophical Society Held at Philadelphia for Promoting Useful Knowledge**.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] Franklin was elected the first president.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] During this time, the society maintained a standing Committee on American Improvements; one of its investigations was to study the prospects for a canal to connect the Chesapeake Bay and the Delaware River.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] The Chesapeake and Delaware Canal, which had been proposed by Thomas Gilpin, Sr., was built in the 1820s.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] Following the American Revolutionary War, the society looked for leadership to Francis Hopkinson, one of the signatories of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] Under his influence, the society received land from the government of Pennsylvania, along with a plot of land in Philadelphia, where Philosophical Hall now stands.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] Charles Darwin, Robert Frost, Louis Pasteur, Elizabeth Cabot Agassiz, John James Audubon, Linus Pauling, Margaret Mead, Woodrow Wilson, Maria Mitchell, and Thomas Edison were all prominent members of the society.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] Many members of the Society of the Cincinnati were among the APS's first board members and contributors; the APS and SOC still maintain an informal, collegial relationship.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] Membership of the APS "honors extraordinary accomplishments in all fields." It has about 1,000 elected members, comprising about 840 "resident" members (United States citizens or those working or living in the United States) and about 160 "international" members.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] As of February 2025 it had elected 5,890 members since its foundation.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] Over that history, 220 members have been from Harvard University, 117 from Princeton University, 91 from Stanford University, and 86 from the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] In 1786, the society established the Magellanic Premium, a prize for achievement in "navigation, astronomy, or natural philosophy," the oldest scientific prize awarded by an American institution, which it still awards.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] The society has published the *Transactions of the American Philosophical Society* since 1771.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] The *Proceedings* have appeared since 1838; they publish the papers delivered at the society's biannual meetings.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] The society has also published *The Papers of Benjamin Franklin*, Joseph Henry, William Penn, and Meriwether Lewis, and William Clark.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] Jane Aitken bound 400 volumes for the society.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] The society also has an expansive archive on framer of the U.S. constitution John Dickinson.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] APS holds the ACLS Collection (American Council of Learned Societies Committee on Native American Languages, American Philosophical Society) which is a collection of indigenous language documents from around the United States including recordings of the Odawa language from northern Michigan.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] APS has created a guide to help provide broad coverage of the Native American and Indigenous archival collections at the Library & Museum of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] These materials date from 1553 to 2020 and include manuscript, audio, and visual materials relating to Indigenous peoples throughout the Americas.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] The society also has a collection of manuscripts on the history of the British colonies, Revolutionary War, the history of American science, quantum physics, Charles Darwin and evolution, genetics and the history of technology.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, at 104 South Fifth Street, Philadelphia, between Chestnut and Walnut Streets, immediately south of Old City Hall, was built in 1785–1789 to house the society and designed by Samuel Vaughan in the Federal style.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] A third floor was added in 1890 to accommodate the expanding library, but was removed in 1948–1950, when the building was restored to its original appearance for the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] In 2001, it was opened to the public as The American Philosophical Society Museum, hosting revolving, thematic exhibitions that explore intersections of history, art, and science.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] The museum features works of art, scientific instruments, original manuscripts, rare books, natural history specimens, and curiosities of all kinds from the APS's own collections, along with objects on loan from other institutions.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] In 1789–90, the Library Company of Philadelphia (LCP)—now located at 1314 Locust Street, Philadelphia—built its headquarters, Library Hall, directly across 5th Street from APS.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] In 1884, LCP sold its building, which was demolished for the expansion of the Drexel & Company Building in 1887.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] The bank building was itself demolished in the 1950s, during the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] In 1958, APS built a new library building on the site, that recreated the façade of LCP's Library Hall.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] APS restored the former Farmers' & Mechanics' Bank building at 425–29 Chestnut Street, which was built in 1854–55 to the design of John M.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] Gries in the Italianate style, to serve as a lecture hall.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] It is the site of meetings and most major events the society hosts.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] Richardson Hall at 431 Chestnut Street, immediately west of Benjamin Franklin Hall, is the former Pennsylvania Company for Insurances on Lives and Granting Annuities Building, which was built between 1871 and 1873 and designed by Addison Hutton.
[src:digby-mclaren/american-philosophical-society] It contains offices and the Consortium for History of Science, Technology and Medicine.
[src:digby-mclaren/andrew-lawson] Lawson was born on July 25, 1861, in Anstruther, Scotland.
[src:digby-mclaren/andrew-lawson] He moved to Hamilton, Ontario, Canada with his parents at age six.
[src:digby-mclaren/andrew-lawson] In 1883, he received his B.A. degree in natural science from the University of Toronto.
[src:digby-mclaren/andrew-lawson] He worked for the Geological Survey of Canada while pursuing his graduate degrees.
[src:digby-mclaren/andrew-lawson] He received his M.A. from the University of Toronto in 1885, and his Ph.D. from Johns Hopkins University in 1888.
[src:digby-mclaren/andrew-lawson] In 1890, he left the Geological Survey of Canada to work as a consulting geologist in Vancouver.
[src:digby-mclaren/andrew-lawson] In October of the same year, he accepted a position as assistant professor of Mineralogy and Geology at the University of California in Berkeley.
[src:digby-mclaren/andrew-lawson] He became a full professor in 1892, and a professor emeritus from 1928 to his death on June 16, 1952.
[src:digby-mclaren/andrew-lawson] Lawson was elected to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1915, the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1924, and the American Philosophical Society in 1925.
[src:digby-mclaren/andrew-lawson] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1926.
[src:digby-mclaren/andrew-lawson] He was a consulting geologist for the construction of the Golden Gate Bridge in the 1930s.
[src:digby-mclaren/andrew-lawson] His home in the La Loma Park area of the Berkeley Hills in Berkeley, California, called the "Andrew Cowper Lawson House" (1908), was especially designed for him by noted architect Bernard Maybeck to withstand earthquakes.
[src:digby-mclaren/andrew-lawson] The house is an official city designated Berkeley Landmark.
[src:digby-mclaren/andrew-lawson] The mineral Lawsonite is named for him, as is the Lawson Adit, originally a mining construction research tunnel on UC Berkeley's campus.
[src:digby-mclaren/andrew-lawson] 13,165 feet) in Sequoia National Park was officially named after him in 1976.
[src:digby-mclaren/andrew-lawson] 1,128 feet), located west of the Briones Hills in Contra Costa County, California, is named for him.
[src:digby-mclaren/digby-mclaren] Born in Carrickfergus, Ireland, and educated at Sedbergh School, he received a Bachelor of Arts in geology from the University of Cambridge.
[src:digby-mclaren/digby-mclaren] During World War II, he fought in the Middle East and Europe with the Royal Regiment of Artillery.
[src:digby-mclaren/digby-mclaren] After the war, he received a Master of Arts in geology from the University of Cambridge in 1948.
[src:digby-mclaren/digby-mclaren] In 1948, he moved to Canada and joined the Geological Survey of Canada (GSC).
[src:digby-mclaren/digby-mclaren] In 1951, he received a Ph.D. from the University of Michigan.
[src:digby-mclaren/digby-mclaren] From 1959 to 1967, he was the head of the palaeontology section of the GSC.
[src:digby-mclaren/digby-mclaren] In 1967, he became the first director of the Institute of Sedimentary and Petroleum Geology of the GSC and in 1973 he was appointed director of the Geological Survey of Canada.
[src:digby-mclaren/digby-mclaren] In 1981, he became Assistant Deputy Minister of Science and Technology for Energy, Mines and Resources Canada.
[src:digby-mclaren/digby-mclaren] He was the author of over 100 publications and maps in the fields of palaeontology, biostratigraphy and regional geology.
[src:digby-mclaren/digby-mclaren] He was one of the early theorists of the Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event.
[src:digby-mclaren/digby-mclaren] From 1987 to 1990, he was the president of the Royal Society of Canada.
[src:digby-mclaren/digby-mclaren] He was also president of the Geological Society of America.
[src:digby-mclaren/digby-mclaren] In 1942, he married Phyllis Matkin, with whom he had three children: Ian, Patrick, and Alison.
